  <subsection>
    <title>Horizontal Lines and Vertical Lines</title>
    <p>
      We learned in <xref ref="section-standard-form"/> that all lines can be written in
      <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="custom">standard form</xref>. When either <m>A</m> or
      <m>B</m> equal <m>0</m>, we end up with a horizontal or vertical line. Let's take the standard
      form line equation, <m>Ax+By=C</m>, and one at a time let <m>A=0</m> and <m>B=0</m> and
      simplify each equation.
    </p>
    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>Ax+By\amp=C\amp Ax+By\amp=C</mrow>
        <mrow>\substitute{0}x+By\amp=C\amp Ax+\substitute{0}y\amp=C</mrow>
        <mrow>By\amp=C\amp Ax\amp=C</mrow>
        <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{C}{B}\amp x\amp=\divideunder{C}{A}</mrow>
        <mrow>y\amp=k\amp x\amp=h</mrow>
      </md>
      At the end we just renamed the constant numbers <m>\frac{C}{B}</m> and <m>\frac{C}{A}</m> to
      <m>k</m> and <m>h</m> because of tradition. What is important, is that you view <m>h</m> and
      <m>k</m> (as well as <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>) as constants: numbers that have some
      specific value and don't change.
    </p>
    <p>
      Think about one of these equations: <m>y=k</m>. It says that the <m>y</m>-value is the same no
      matter where you are on the line. If you wanted to plot points on this line, you are free to
      move to the left or to the right on the <m>x</m>-axis, but then you always move up (or down)
      by the same amount to make the <m>y</m>-value reach <m>k</m>. What does such a line look like?
    </p>
    <example>
      <p>
        Let's plot the line with equation <m>y=3</m>. To plot some points, it doesn't matter
        what <m>x</m>-values we use. All that matters is that <m>y</m> is always <m>3</m>.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="figure-horizontal-line">
        <caption><m>y=3</m></caption>
        <image width="47%">
          <shortdescription>
            a horizontal line at y=3
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="horizontal-line-standard-form">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                ]
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(4,0) (5,0) (5,3)};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0) (1,3)};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-1,0) (-2,0) (-2,3)};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-5,0) (-6,0) (-6,3)};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(5,3) (1,3) (-2,3) (-6,3)};
                \addplot[firstcurve]{3};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </example>
    <p>
      A line like the one in <xref ref="figure-horizontal-line"/> is <term>horizontal</term>. It is           <idx><h>Horizontal line</h></idx>
      parallel to the horizontal axis. All the <m>y</m>-values of points on a horizontal line are
      the same. All lines with an equation in the form <m>y=k</m> are horizontal lines.                       <idx><h>Equation of a line</h><h>horizontal line</h></idx>
    </p>
    <example>
      <p>
        Let's plot the line with equation <m>x=5</m>. Points on the line always have <m>x=5</m>,
        so to make a graph, we must move right to <m>5</m> on the <m>x</m>-axis. From there, it does
        not matter if we move up or down, we would still be at a place where <m>x=5</m>.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="figure-vertical-line-example">
        <caption><m>x=5</m></caption>
        <image width="47%">
          <shortdescription>a vertical line at x=5</shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="vertical-line-standard-form">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                ]
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(5,0) (5,5)};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(5,0) (5,1)};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(5,0) (5,-2)};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(5,0) (5,-6)};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (5,0)};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(5,5) (5,1) (5,-2) (5,-6)};
                \addplot[firstcurve] coordinates {(5,-7) (5,7)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        A line like this is <term>vertical</term>, parallel to the vertical axis. All lines with an           <idx><h>Vertical line</h></idx>
        equation in the form <m>x=h</m> (or, in standard form, <m>Ax+0y=C</m>) are vertical.                  <idx><h>Equation of a line</h><h>vertical line</h></idx>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      A line like the one in <xref ref="figure-vertical-line-example"/> is <term>vertical</term>. It
      is parallel to the vertical axis. All the <m>y</m>-values of points on a vertical line are
      the same. All lines with an equation in the form <m>x=h</m> are vertical lines.
    </p>

    <example>
      <title>Zero Slope</title>                                                                               <idx><h>Horizontal line</h><h>slope of</h></idx>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="exercise-jogging-on-mt-hood"/>, we learned that a horizontal line's slope is
        <m>0</m>, because the <m>y</m>-values don't change as time moves on. So the numerator in the
        <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="custom">slope formula</xref> is <m>0</m>. Now, if
        we know a line's slope and its <m>y</m>-intercept, we can use
        <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref> to write
        its equation:
        <md>
          <mrow>y\amp=mx+b</mrow>
          <mrow>y\amp=0x+b</mrow>
          <mrow>y\amp=b</mrow>
        </md>
        This gives us an alternative way to think about equations of horizontal lines. They have a
        certain <m>y</m>-intercept <m>b</m>, and they have slope <m>0</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We use horizontal lines to model scenarios where there is no change in <m>y</m>-values, like
        when Kato stopped for <m>12</m> hours (he deserved a rest)!
      </p>
    </example>
    <exercise>
      <title>Plotting Points</title>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          @x=(-2..2);
          @y=(-4.25)x5;
          $pts=MultiAnswer(map{($_%2==0)?$x[$_/2]:$y[($_-1)/2]}(0..9))->with(
            singleResult => 1,
            allowBlankAnswers => 1,
            checker => sub {
              my ($correct,$student,$self) = @_;
              my @sx = @{$student}[0,2,4,6,8];
              my @sy = @{$student}[1,3,5,7,9];
              my $OK=1;
              if ($sy[0]!=-4.25) {
                  $self->setMessage(1,"This point is not on the line.");
                  $self->setMessage(2,"This point is not on the line.");
                  $OK=0;
                }
              for my $i(1..4){
                if ($sy[$i]!=-4.25) {
                  $self->setMessage(2*$i+1,"This point is not on the line.");
                  $self->setMessage(2*$i+2,"This point is not on the line.");
                  $OK=0;
                }
                for my $j(0..$i-1){
                  if ($sy[$i]==-4.25 and $sx[$i]==$sx[$j]) {
                    $self->setMessage(2*$i+1,"This point was already used.");
                    $self->setMessage(2*$i+2,"This point was already used.");
                    $OK=0;
                  }
                }
              }
              return $OK;
            }
          );
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose you need to plot the equation <m>y=-4.25</m>. Since the equation is in
            <q><m>y=</m></q> form, you decide to make a table of points. Fill out some points for
            this table.
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium" halign="center">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We can use whatever values for <m>x</m> that we like, as long as they are all different.
            The equation tells us the <m>y</m>-value has to be <m>-4.25</m> each time.
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium" halign="center">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-4.25</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-4.25</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-4.25</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-4.25</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-4.25</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            Now that we have a table, we could use its values to assist with plotting the line.
          </p>
          <image width="47%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+ {-4.25};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,-4.25) (-1,-4.25) (0,-4.25) (1,-4.25) (2,-4.25)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <example>
      <title>Slope of a Vertical Line</title>
      <p>
        What is the slope of a vertical line? <xref ref="figure-vertical-lines"/> shows three lines
        passing through the origin, each steeper than the last. In each graph, you can see a slope
        triangle that uses a <q>run</q> of <m>1</m> unit.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="figure-vertical-lines">
        <caption></caption>
        <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%">
          <image>
            <shortdescription>a line with a slope of 1/1=1</shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="line-with-slope-1">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-1,
                    ymin=-1,
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[] coordinates {(-1,-1) (7,7)} node[above,sloped,pos=0.5] {slope is $1$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0)} node[below,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,0) (1,1)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              a line with a slope of 2/1=2, which is steeper than the first line
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="line-with-slope-2">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-1,
                    ymin=-1,
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[] coordinates {(-0.5,-1) (3.5,7)} node[above,sloped,pos=0.5] {slope is $2$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0)} node[below,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,0) (1,2)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$2$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              a line with a slope of 4/1=4, which is steeper than the previous two lines
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="line-with-slope-4">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-1,
                    ymin=-1,
                    width=0.32\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[] coordinates {(-0.25,-1) (1.75,7)} node[above,sloped,pos=0.75] {slope is $4$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0)} node[below,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,0) (1,4)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$4$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </sidebyside>
      </figure>
      <p>
        If we continued making the line steeper and steeper until it was vertical, the slope
        triangle would still have a <q>run</q> of <m>1</m>, but the <q>rise</q> would become larger
        and larger with no upper limit. The slope would be <m>m=\frac{\text{very large}}{1}</m>.
        Actually if the line is vertical, the <q>rise</q> segment we've drawn will never make
        contact with the line. So there won't be any <q>rise</q> to correspond with that <q>run</q>.
        We usually say that the slope of a vertical line is <em>undefined</em>. You can also say
        that a vertical line <q>has no slope</q>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <fact xml:id="fact-undefined-slope">                                                                      <idx><h>Slope</h><h>undefined</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Undefined</h><h>slope</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Vertical line</h><h>slope of</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The slope of a vertical line is undefined.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <remark>
      <p>
        Be careful not to mix up <q>no slope</q> (which means <q>its slope is undefined</q>) with
        <q>has slope <m>0</m></q>. If a line has slope <m>0</m>, it <em>does</em> have a slope.
      </p>
      <p>
        In sports, some players wear number <m>0</m>. That's not the same thing as not having a
        number. This is similar to the situation where having slope <m>0</m> means you do have a
        slope, and is different from not having a slope.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <exercise>
      <title>Plotting Points</title>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          @x=(3.14)x5;
          @y=(-2..2);
          $pts=MultiAnswer(map{($_%2==0)?$x[$_/2]:$y[($_-1)/2]}(0..9))->with(
            singleResult => 1,
            allowBlankAnswers => 1,
            checker => sub {
              my ($correct,$student,$self) = @_;
              my @sx = @{$student}[0,2,4,6,8];
              my @sy = @{$student}[1,3,5,7,9];
              my $OK=1;
              if ($sx[0]!=3.14) {
                  $self->setMessage(1,"This point is not on the line.");
                  $self->setMessage(2,"This point is not on the line.");
                  $OK=0;
                }
              for my $i(1..4){
                if ($sx[$i]!=3.14) {
                  $self->setMessage(2*$i+1,"This point is not on the line.");
                  $self->setMessage(2*$i+2,"This point is not on the line.");
                  $OK=0;
                }
                for my $j(0..$i-1){
                  if ($sx[$i]==3.14 and $sy[$i]==$sy[$j]) {
                    $self->setMessage(2*$i+1,"This point was already used.");
                    $self->setMessage(2*$i+2,"This point was already used.");
                    $OK=0;
                  }
                }
              }
              return $OK;
            }
          );
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose you need to plot the equation <m>x=3.14</m>. You decide to try making a table of
            points. Fill out some points for this table.
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium" halign="center">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
              <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Since the equation says <m>x</m> is always the number <m>3.14</m>, we have to use this
            for the <m>x</m> value in all the points. This is different from how we would plot a
            <q><m>y=</m></q> equation, where we would use several different <m>x</m>-values. We can
            use whatever values for <m>y</m> that we like, as long as they are all different.
          </p>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium" halign="center">
              <cell><m>x</m></cell>
              <cell><m>y</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>3.14</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>3.14</m></cell>
              <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>3.14</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>3.14</m></cell>
              <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>3.14</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
          <p>
            The reason we made a table was to help with plotting the line.
          </p>
          <image width="47%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+ coordinates {(3.14,-7) (3.14,7)};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3.14,-2) (3.14,-1) (3.14,0) (3.14,1) (3.14,2)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <example>
      <p>
        Let <m>x</m> represent the price of a new <m>60</m>-inch television at Target on Black
        Friday (which was <m>\$650</m>), and let <m>y</m> be the number of hours you will watch
        something on this TV over its lifetime. What is the relationship between <m>x</m> and
        <m>y</m>?
      </p>
      <p>
        Well, there is no getting around the fact that <m>x=650</m>. As for <m>y</m>, without any
        extra information about your viewing habits, it could theoretically be as low as <m>0</m>
        or it could be anything larger than that. If we graph this scenario, we have to graph the
        equation <m>x=650</m> which we now know to give a vertical line, and we get
        <xref ref="figure-television"/>.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="figure-television">
        <caption>
          New TV: hours watched versus purchase price; negative <m>y</m>-values omitted since they
          make no sense in context
        </caption>
        <image width="100%">
          <shortdescription>
            the vertical line x=650, starting at the point (650,0) with an arrow pointing upward
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="television">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  xmin=0,
                  xmax=1000,
                  ymin=0,
                  ymax=1000,
                  xtick={200,400,...,800},
                  minor xtick={100,300,...,900},
                  ytick={200,400,...,800},
                  minor ytick={100,300,...,900},
                  ylabel={hours watched},
                  xlabel={purchase price},
                  width=\orccaprintwidth,
                  height=0.33\orccaprintwidth,
                  axis line style={->},
                ]
                \addplot+[->] coordinates {(650,0) (650,1000)};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(650,0)};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </example>

    <figure>
      <caption>Summary of Horizontal and Vertical Line Equations</caption>
      <sidebyside>
        <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
          <col width="47%" right="medium"/>
          <col width="47%" />
          <row bottom="medium" header="yes">
            <cell>Horizontal Lines</cell>
            <cell>Vertical Lines</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>
              <p>
                A line is <term>horizontal</term> if and only if its equation can be written
                <me>
                  y=k
                </me>
                for some constant <m>k</m>.
              </p>
            </cell>
            <cell>
              <p>
                A line is <term>vertical</term> if and only if its equation can be written
                <me>
                  x=h
                </me>
                for some constant <m>h</m>.
              </p>
            </cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>
              <p>
                In <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="custom">standard form</xref>, any line
                with equation
                <me>
                  0x+By=C
                </me>
                is horizontal.
              </p>
            </cell>
            <cell>
              <p>
                In <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="custom">standard form</xref>, any line
                with equation
                <me>
                  Ax+0y=C
                </me>
                is vertical.
              </p>
            </cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>
              <p>
                If the line with equation <m>y=k</m> is horizontal, it has a <m>y</m>-intercept at
                <m>(0,k)</m> and has slope <m>0</m>.
              </p>
            </cell>
            <cell>
              <p>
                If the line with equation <m>x=h</m> is vertical, it has an <m>x</m>-intercept at
                <m>(h,0)</m> and its slope is <em>undefined</em>. Some say it has <em>no</em> slope,
                and some say the slope is <em>infinitely large</em>.
              </p>
            </cell>
          </row>
          <row bottom="none">
            <cell>
              <p>
                In the
                <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref>,
                any line with equation
                <me>
                  y=0x+b
                </me>
                is horizontal.
              </p>
            </cell>
            <cell>
              <p>
                It's impossible to write the equation of a vertical line in
                <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref>,
                because vertical lines do not have a defined slope.
              </p>
            </cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsection-parallel-lines">
    <title>Parallel Lines</title>
    <p>
      What makes two lines parallel?
    </p>
    <example>
      <p>
        Two trees were planted in the same year, and their growth over time is modeled by the
        two lines in <xref ref="figure-trees"/>. Use linear equations to model each tree's
        growth, and interpret their meanings in this context.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="figure-trees">
        <caption>Two Trees' Growth Chart</caption>
        <image width="100%">
          <shortdescription>
            This is a Cartesian grid with two parallel lines. Tree 1 has a slope triangle from
            (0,2) to (3,4) for a slope of 2/3. Tree 2 has a slope triangle from (0,5) to (3.7) for
            a slope of 2/3.
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="trees-growth-chart">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  xlabel={$x$ time in years},
                  ylabel={$y$ height in feet},
                  xmin=0,
                  xmax=5,
                  ymin=0,
                  ymax=9,
                  minor ytick=,
                  xtick={-1,0,...,4},
                  ytick={-1,0,...,8},
                  width=\orccaprintwidth,
                  height=0.33\orccaprintwidth,
                  axis line style={->},
                ]
                \addplot+[domain = 0:5,->]{2/3*x+2} node[pos=0.3,sloped,above] {Tree 1};
                \addplot+[domain = 0:5,->]{2/3*x+5} node[pos=0.3,sloped,above] {Tree 2};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,2)} node[below right] {$(0,2)$};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,4)} node[below right] {$(3,4)$};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,2) (3,2)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$3$};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,2) (3,3.7)} node[pos=0.5,left] {$2$};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[below right] {$(0,5)$};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,7)} node[below right] {$(3,7)$};
                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,5) (3,5)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$3$};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,5) (3,6.7)} node[pos=0.5,left] {$2$};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        We can see Tree 1's equation is <m>y=\frac{2}{3}x+2</m>, and Tree 2's equation is
        <m>y=\frac{2}{3}x+5</m>. Both trees have been growing at the same rate, <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>
        feet per year, or <m>2</m> feet every <m>3</m> years. The two lines have the same slope
        <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>. No matter which line we look at, moving rightward <m>3</m> units causes
        us to move upward <m>2</m> units, and so the two lines will never meet. They are parallel.
      </p>
    </example>

    <fact xml:id="fact-parallel-lines">                                                                       <idx><h>Parallel lines</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Parallel lines</h><h>and slope</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Slope</h><h>and parallel lines</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For any two non-vertical lines, they are parallel if and only if they have the same slope.
          (And any two vertical lines are parallel to each other.)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>

    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
          parser::Assignment->Allow;
          $line=Formula("y=17.2x+128.2");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A line <m>\ell</m> is parallel to the line with equation <m>y=17.2x-340.9</m>, but
            <m>\ell</m> has <m>y</m>-intercept at <m>(0,128.2)</m>. What is an equation for
            <m>\ell</m>?
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$line" width="20" />
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Parallel lines have the same slope, and the slope of <m>y=17.2x-340.9</m> is
            <m>17.2</m>. So <m>\ell</m> has slope <m>17.2</m>. And we have been given that
            <m>\ell</m>'s <m>y</m>-intercept is at <m>(0,128.2)</m>. So we can use slope-intercept
            form to write its equation as
            <me>
              y=17.2x+128.2
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
          parser::Assignment->Allow;
          $line=Formula("y=-3.5(x+12)+23");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A line <m>\kappa</m> is parallel to the line with equation <m>y=-3.5x+17</m>,
            but <m>\kappa</m> passes through the point <m>(-12,23)</m>.
            What is an equation for <m>\kappa</m>?
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$line" width="20" />
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Parallel lines have the same slope, and the slope of <m>y=-3.5x+17</m> is <m>-3.5</m>.
            So <m>\kappa</m> has slope <m>-3.5</m>. And we know a point that <m>\kappa</m> passes
            through, so we can use point-slope form to write its equation as
            <me>
              y=-3.5(x+12)+23
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Perpendicular Lines</title>
    <p>
      The slopes of two perpendicular lines have a special relationship too.
      <xref ref="figure-perpendicular-lines"/> walks you through an explanation of this
      relationship.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-perpendicular-lines">
      <caption>The relationship between slopes of perpendicular lines</caption>
      <sidebyside widths="31% 31% 31%" margins="0%">
        <figure>
          <caption>Two generic perpendicular lines, where one has slope <m>m</m>.</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              the graph of two perpendicular lines, where one has a slope of m
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="generic-perpendicular-lines">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-2,
                    ymin=-2,
                    ticks=none,
                    xmajorticks=false,
                    ymajorticks=false,
                    grid=none,
                    axis equal,
                    width=0.31\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain=-2:7]{0.5*x+2.5} node[pos=0.7,sloped,above] {slope $m$};
                  \addplot+[domain=-1:3.5]{-2*x+5};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <figure>
          <caption>
            Since the one slope is <m>m</m>, we can draw a slope triangle with <q>run</q> <m>1</m>
            and <q>rise</q> <m>m</m>.
          </caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              the previous graph with a slope triangle added; the rise is m and the run is 1
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="generic-perpendicular-lines-with-slope-triangles">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-2,
                    ymin=-2,
                    ticks=none,
                    xmajorticks=false,
                    ymajorticks=false,
                    grid=none,
                    axis equal,
                    width=0.31\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain=-2:7]{0.5*x+2.5};
                  \addplot+[domain=-1:3.5]{-2*x+5};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,3) (5,3)} node[below,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(5,3) (5,5)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$m$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <figure>
          <caption>
            A <em>congruent</em> slope triangle can be drawn for the perpendicular line. It's legs
            have the same lengths, but in different positions, and one is negative.
          </caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              the previous graph with the perpendicular line and its slope triangle added; the
              perpendicular line has a rise of -1 and a run of m which gives a slope of -1/m
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="generic-perpendicular-lines-with-slope-triangles-congruent">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-2,
                    ymin=-2,
                    ticks=none,
                    xmajorticks=false,
                    ymajorticks=false,
                    grid=none,
                    axis equal,
                    width=0.31\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain=-2:7]{0.5*x+2.5};
                  \addplot+[domain=-1:3.5]{-2*x+5};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,-1) (3,-1)} node[below,pos=0.5] {$m$};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,3) (1,-1)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$-1$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>

    <p>
      When the first line in <xref ref="figure-perpendicular-lines"/> has slope  <m>m</m>, the
      second has slope
      <me>
        \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{-1}{m}=-\frac{1}{m}
      </me>.
    </p>

    <fact xml:id="fact-perpendicular-lines">                                                                  <idx><h>Perpendicular lines</h></idx>
                                                                                                              <idx><h>Slope</h><h>and perpendicular lines</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For two lines that are neither vertical nor horizontal, they are perpendicular to each              <idx><h>Reciprocal</h><h>negative</h></idx>
          other if and only if the slope of one is the <em>negative reciprocal</em> of the slope of           <idx><h>Negative reciprocals</h></idx>
          the other. That is, if one has slope <m>m</m>, the other has slope <m>-\frac{1}{m}</m>.             <idx><h>Perpendicular lines</h><h>and slope</h></idx>
          (And a vertical line and a horizontal line are always perpendicular to each other.)
        </p>

        <p>
          Another way to say this is that the product of the slopes of two perpendicular lines is
          <m>-1</m> (assuming both of the lines have a slope in the first place). That is, if there
          are two perpendicular lines and we let <m>m_1</m> and <m>m_2</m> represent their slopes,
          then <m>m_1\cdot m_2=-1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </fact>
    <p>
      Here are three pairs of perpendicular lines where we can see if the pattern holds.
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="31% 31% 31%" margins="0%">
      <figure>
        <caption>
          <m>y=2x-2</m> and <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x+2</m>. Note the relationship between their
          slopes: <m>2\cdot-\frac{1}{2}=-1</m>
        </caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            the graph of lines y=2x-2 and y=-1/2x+2 showing that they are perpendicular lines.
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="specific-perpendicular-lines-1">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  axis equal,
                  width=0.31\orccaprintwidth,
                ]
                \addplot+[domain = -2.5:4.5]{2*x-2};
                \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{-0.5*x+2};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure>
        <caption>
          <m>y=-3x+4</m> and <m>y=\frac{1}{3}x-3</m>. Note the relationship between their
          slopes: <m>-3\cdot\frac{1}{3}=-1</m>
        </caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            the graph of lines y=-3x+4 and y=1/3x-3 showing that they are perpendicular
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="specific-perpendicular-lines-2">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  axis equal,
                  width=0.31\orccaprintwidth,
                ]
                \addplot+[domain = -1:3.666]{-3*x+4};
                \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{1/3*x-3};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure>
        <caption>
          <m>y=x</m> and <m>y=-x</m>. Note the relationship between their slopes:
          <m>1\cdot-1=-1</m>
        </caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            the graph of lines y=x and y=-x showing that they are perpendicular
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="specific-perpendicular-lines-3">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  axis equal,
                  width=0.31\orccaprintwidth,
                ]
                \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{x};
                \addplot+[domain = -7:7]{-x};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </sidebyside>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Line <m>A</m> passes through <m>(-2,10)</m> and <m>(3,-10)</m>. Line <m>B</m> passes
          through <m>(-4,-4)</m> and <m>(8,-1)</m>. Determine whether these two lines are parallel,
          perpendicular or neither.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We will use the slope formula to find both lines' slopes:
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{Line }A\text{'s slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}\amp\text{Line }B\text{'s slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10-10}{3-(-2)}\amp\amp=\frac{-1-(-4)}{8-(-4)}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-20}{5}\amp\amp=\frac{3}{12}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-4\amp\amp=\frac{1}{4}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Their slopes are not the same, so those two lines are not parallel.
        </p>
        <p>
          The product of their slopes is <m>(-4)\cdot\frac{1}{4}=-1</m>, which means the two lines
          are perpendicular.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <pg-code>
          Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y=>'Real');
          parser::Assignment->Allow;
          $line=Formula("y=3/2(x-4)-3");
        </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Line <m>A</m> and Line <m>B</m> are perpendicular. Line <m>A</m>'s equation is
            <m>2x+3y=12</m>. Line <m>B</m> passes through the point <m>(4,-3)</m>. Find an equation
            for Line <m>B</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <var name="$line" width="20" />
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            First, we will find Line <m>A</m>'s slope by rewriting its equation from standard form
            to slope-intercept form:
            <md>
              <mrow>2x+3y\amp=12</mrow>
              <mrow>3y\amp=12\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
              <mrow>3y\amp=-2x+12</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{-2x+12}{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x+4</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            So Line <m>A</m>'s slope is <m>-\frac{2}{3}</m>. Since Line <m>B</m> is perpendicular to
            Line <m>A</m>, its slope is the negative reciprocal, <m>\frac{3}{2}</m>. It's also given
            that Line <m>B</m> passes through <m>(4,-3)</m>, so we can write Line <m>B</m>'s
            point-slope form equation:
            <md>
              <mrow>y\amp=m(x-x_0)+y_0</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{3}{2}(x-4)-3</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

